8
00:00:33,410 --> 00:00:38,280
But that story connects up to the ancient law of the sea, which

9
00:00:38,280 --> 00:00:40,930
even today is respected.

10
00:00:40,930 --> 00:00:45,510
The ancient law of the sea addresses this problem.

11
00:00:45,510 --> 00:00:47,750
You&#39;ve got a storm at sea.

12
00:00:47,750 --> 00:00:52,470
You have a cargo, which is in peril, and the master of the ship

13
00:00:52,470 --> 00:00:58,990
reasonably decides that in order to survive-- in order for the sailors,

14
00:00:58,990 --> 00:01:03,890
and for the passengers, and for any of the cargo to survive,

15
00:01:03,890 --> 00:01:09,530
they&#39;ve got to throw a significant part of the cargo overboard.

16
00:01:09,530 --> 00:01:12,350
They&#39;ve got to lighten the ship.

17
00:01:12,350 --> 00:01:13,870
And that&#39;s what they do.

18
00:01:13,870 --> 00:01:19,790
The ship survives, they put into port, and they unload the remaining cargo.

19
00:01:19,790 --> 00:01:22,710
Well, what about those people whose cargo

20
00:01:22,710 --> 00:01:26,110
was thrown overboard to save the ship?

21
00:01:26,110 --> 00:01:28,490
Are they just out of luck?

22
00:01:28,490 --> 00:01:33,530
Maybe some of them had very heavy cargo, and so that&#39;s

23
00:01:33,530 --> 00:01:37,980
why the master quite reasonably decided to throw it overboard.

24
00:01:37,980 --> 00:01:41,250
And the others had lighter but much more valuable

25
00:01:41,250 --> 00:01:47,320
cargo-- let&#39;s say silk or spices-- and that&#39;s what survived.

26
00:01:47,320 --> 00:01:52,810
Could we just say that the folks whose stuff was thrown overboard

27
00:01:52,810 --> 00:01:56,860
